{{Health care reform in the United States}}
The issue of '''health insurance reform in the United States''' has been the subject of political debate since the early part of the 20th century.  Recent reforms remains an active political issue.  Alternative reform proposals were offered by both of the two major candidates in the [[United States presidential election, 2008|2008 presidential election]].

==Federal reform efforts==

=== 19th century ===
One of the earliest health care proposals at the federal level was the 1854 [[Bill for the Benefit of the Indigent Insane]], which would have established asylums for the indigent insane, as well as the blind, and deaf via federal land grants to the states. This bill was proposed by activist [[Dorothea Dix]], which passed both houses of congress, but was vetoed by president [[Franklin Pierce]]. Pierce argued that the federal government should not commit itself to [[social welfare]], which he believed was properly the responsibility of the states.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pierce|first=Franklin|date=May 3, 1854|title=Veto message|location=Livonia, Mich.|publisher=LONANG (Laws Of Nature And Nature's God) Institute|url=http://www.lonang.com/exlibris/misc/1854-pvm.htm|accessdate=March 22, 2010}}</ref><ref name="Tiffany 1890">{{cite book|last=Tiffany|first=Francis|year=1890|title=The life of Dorothea Lynde Dix|location=Boston|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|page=180|oclc=251005|accessdate=March 22, 2010|isbn=0-217-96357-9}}</ref> After the Civil War, the federal government did establish the first system of national medical care in the South. Known as the Freedmen's Bureau, the government constructed 40 hospitals, employed over 120 physicians, and treated well over one million sick and dying former slaves. The hospitals were short lived, lasting from 1865 to 1870. Freedmen's Hospital in Washington, DC remained in operation until the late nineteenth-century before it became part of Howard University.<ref>Jim Downs, Sick from Freedom, First Edition, New York, Oxford University Press, 2012,</ref>

The next major initiative came in the [[New Deal]] legislation of the 1930s, in the context of the [[Great Depression]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Manning|first=Seaton W.|month=March |year=1962|title=The tragedy of the Ten-million-acre bill|journal=Social Service Review|volume=36|issue=1|pages=44–50|doi=10.1086/641182|accessdate=March 22, 2010}}</ref>

=== 1900s-1920s ===
In the first 10–15 years of the 20th century Progressivism was influencing both Europe and the United States.<ref name="Derickson 2005">{{cite book|last=Derickson|first=Alan|year=2005|title=Health security for all: dreams of universal health care in America|location=Baltimore|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|isbn=0-8018-8081-5}}</ref> Many European countries were passing the first social welfare acts and forming the basis for compulsory government-run or voluntary subsidized health care programs.<ref name="Patel 2006">{{cite book|last1=Patel|first1=Kant|last2=Rushefsky|first2=Mark E.|year=2006|title=Health care politics and policy in America|edition=3rd|location=Armonk, N.Y.|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|pages=34–74|isbn=0-7656-1478-2}}</ref> The United Kingdom passed the National Insurance Act of 1911 that provided medical care and replacement of some lost wages if a worker became ill. It did not, however, cover spouses or dependents. U.S. efforts to achieve universal coverage began with [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who had the support of [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] health care reformers in the 1912 election but was defeated.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Igel|first=Lee|month=May–June|year=2008|title=The history of health care as a campaign issue|journal=Physician Executive|volume=34|issue=3|pages=12–15|pmid=18605264|url=http://net.acpe.org/MembersOnly/pejournal/2008/MayJun/Igel.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2009}}</ref> Progressives campaigned unsuccessfully for sickness insurance guaranteed by the states.<ref name="Walker 1979">{{cite journal|last=Walker|first=Forrest A.|month=Winter|year=1979|title=Americanism versus sovietism: a study of the reaction to the Committee on the Costs of Medical Care|journal=Bulletin of the History of Medicine|volume=53|issue=4|pages=489–504|pmid=397839}}</ref> A unique American history of decentralization in government, limited government, and a tradition of classical liberalism are all possible explanations for the suspicion around the idea of compulsory government-run insurance.<ref name="Patel 2006"/> The American Medical Association (AMA) was also deeply and vocally opposed to the idea.<ref name="Walker 1979"/> In addition, many urban US workers already had access to sickness insurance through employer-based sickness funds.

Early industrial sickness insurance purchased through employers was one influential economic origin of the current American health care system.<ref name="Murray 2007">{{cite book|last=Murray|first=John E.|year=2007|title=Origins of American health insurance: a history of industrial sickness funds|location=New Haven|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0-300-12091-5}}</ref> These late-19th-century and early-20th-century sickness insurance schemes were generally inexpensive for workers: their small scale and local administration kept overhead low, and because the people who purchased insurance were all employees of the same company, that prevented people who were already ill from buying in.<ref name="Murray 2007"/> The presence of employer-based sickness funds may have contributed to why the idea of government-based insurance did not take hold in the United States at the same time that the United Kingdom and the rest of Europe was moving toward socialized schemes like the UK National Insurance Act of 1911.<ref name="Murray 2007"/> Thus, at the beginning of the 20th century, Americans were used to associating insurance with employers, which paved the way for the beginning of third party health insurance in the 1930s.

=== 1930s-1950s ===
[[File:Letter from Harry S. Truman to Ben Turoff - NARA - 201512.tif|thumb|Letter from President [[Harry Truman]] defending his [[Fair Deal]] proposal for a national compulsory health insurance program.<ref>{{cite web|last=Truman|first=Harry S.|date=April 12, 1949|title=Letter from Harry S. Truman to Ben Turoff|location=College Park, Md.|publisher=National Archives and Records Administration|url=http://arcweb.archives.gov/arc/action/ExternalIdSearch?id=201512|accessdate=December 2, 2011}}
* {{cite book|last1=Truman|first1=Harry S.|last2=Poen|first2=Monte M. (ed.)|year=1982|title=Strictly personal and confidential: the letters Harry Truman never mailed|location=Boston|publisher=Little, Brown|pages=96–97|isbn=0-316-71221-3}}</ref>]]
With the [[Great Depression]], more and more people could not afford medical services.  In 1933, [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] asked Isidore Falk and Edgar Sydenstricter to help draft provisions to Roosevelt's pending [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] legislation to include [[publicly funded health care]] programs. These reforms were attacked by the [[American Medical Association]] as well as state and local affiliates of the AMA as "compulsory health insurance." Roosevelt ended up removing the health care provisions from the bill in 1935. Fear of organized medicine's opposition to [[universal health care]] became standard for decades after the 1930s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Coombs|first=Jan|year=2005|title=The rise and fall of HMOs: an American health care revolution|location=Madison|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|pages=5–6|isbn=0-299-20240-2|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=tK71nX5LxSEC&pg=PA5|accessdate=May 31, 2009}}</ref>

During this time, individual hospitals began offering their own insurance programs, the first of which became Blue Cross.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sultz|first1=Harry A.|last2=Young|first2=Kristina M.|year=2011|title=Health care USA: understanding its organization and delivery|edition=7th|location=Sudbury, Mass.|publisher=Jones & Bartlett Learning|pages=35–37, 230–232|isbn=0-7637-8458-3}}</ref> Groups of hospitals as well as physician groups (i.e. Blue Shield) soon began selling group health insurance policies to employers, who then offered them to their employees and collected premiums.  In the 1940s Congress passed legislation that supported the new third-party insurers.  During World War II, Henry Kaiser used an arrangement in which doctors by passed tradition fee-for-care and were contracted to meet all the medical needs for his employees on construction projects up and down the West coast.<ref>{{cite book|last=Falkson|first=Joseph L.|year=1980|title=HMOs and the politics of health system reform|location=Chicago|publisher=American Hospital Association|isbn=0-87258-288-4}}</ref> After the war ended, he opened the plan up to the public as a non-profit organization under the name Kaiser Permanente.

Following the second world war, President [[Harry Truman]] called for universal health care as a part of his [[Fair Deal]] in 1949 but strong opposition stopped that part of the Fair Deal.<ref>{{cite web|last=Geselbracht|first=Raymond H.|year=1999|title=The Truman administration during 1949: a chronology, part two|location=Independence, Mo.|publisher=[[Harry S. Truman Presidential Library and Museum|Harry S. Truman Library and Museum]]|url=http://www.trumanlibrary.org/chron/49chron2.htm#fair|accessdate=October 7, 2009}}<br/>In 1949, as part of his Fair Deal:
*On April 24, 1949, The [[American Medical Association]] denounced this health program.
*On April 25, 1949, The Murray-Dingell omnibus health legislation (S.1679 and H.R. 4312) were introduced into the Senate and the House; the Congress adjourned in October 1949 without acting on these bills.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Poen|first=Monte M.|year=1979, 1996|title=Harry S. Truman versus the medical lobby: the genesis of Medicare|location=Columbia|publisher=University of Missouri Press|pages=161–168|isbn=0-8262-1086-4|accessdate=October 8, 2009}}</ref> However, in 1946 the [[National Mental Health Act]] was passed, as was the Hospital Survey and Construction Act, or [[Hill-Burton Act]]. In 1951 the IRS declared group premiums paid by employers as a tax-deductible business expense,<ref name="Patel 2006"/> which solidified the third-party insurance companies' place as primary providers of access to health care in the United States.

=== 1960s-1980s ===

==== 1960s ====
In the Civil Rights era of the 1960s and early 1970s, public opinion shifted towards the problem of the uninsured, especially the elderly. Since care for the elderly would someday affect everyone, supporters of health care reform were able to avoid the worst fears of "socialized medicine," which was considered a dirty word for its association with communism.<ref name="Patel 2006"/> After Lyndon B. Johnson was elected president in 1964, the stage was set for the passage of Medicare and Medicaid in 1965.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Falk|first=I.S.|month=Winter|year=1973|title=Medical care in the USA—1932–1972. Problems, proposals and programs from the Committee on the Costs of Medical Care to the Committee for National Health Insurance|journal=Milbank Memorial Fund Quarterly. Health and Society|volume=51|issue=1|pages=1–32|jstor=3349608|pmid=4579461}}</ref> Johnson's plan was not without opposition, however. "Opponents, especially the AMA and insurance companies, opposed the Johnson administration's proposal on the grounds that it was compulsory, it represented socialized medicine, it would reduce the quality of care, and it was 'un-American.'"<ref name="Patel 2006"/> These views notwithstanding, the [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] program was established by legislation signed into law on July 30, 1965, by President Lyndon B. Johnson. Medicare is a social insurance program administered by the United States government, providing health insurance coverage to people who are either age 65 and over, or who meet other special criteria.

==== 1970s ====
In 1970, three proposals for [[universal health care|universal]] [[national health insurance]] financed by payroll taxes and general federal revenues were introduced in the U.S. Congress.<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1970">{{cite book|author=.|year=1971|chapter=National health insurance|title=Congressional Quarterly almanac, 91st Congress 2nd session....1970|volume=26|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Congressional Quarterly|pages=603–605|issn=0095-6007|oclc=1564784}}</ref> In February 1970, Representative [[Martha Griffiths]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Michigan's 17th congressional district|MI]]) introduced a national health insurance bill—without any [[cost sharing]]—developed with the [[AFL–CIO]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Stetson|first=Damon|date=February 18, 1970 |title=Labor council supports national health insurance|newspaper=The New York Times|page=8 |url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10A1EF63F5E1A718DDDA10994DA405B808BF1D3}}</ref> In April 1970, Senator [[Jacob K. Javits|Jacob Javits]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[List of United States Senators from New York|NY]]) introduced a bill to extend [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] to all—retaining existing Medicare cost sharing and coverage limits—developed after consultation with Governor [[Nelson Rockefeller]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[List of Governors of New York|NY]]) and former Johnson administration [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services#List of Secretaries|HEW Secretary]] [[Wilbur J. Cohen|Wilbur Cohen]].<ref>{{cite news|author=.|date=April 15, 1970 |title=Medicare for all is asked by Javits|newspaper=The New York Times|page=18|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60B17FD3E5C1A7493C7A8178FD85F448785F9}}</ref> In August 1970, Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[List of United States Senators from Massachusetts|MA]]) introduced a bipartisan national health insurance bill—without any cost sharing—developed with the Committee for National Health Insurance founded by [[United Auto Workers]] (UAW) president [[Walter Reuther]], with a corresponding bill introduced in the House the following month by Representative [[James C. Corman|James Corman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[California's 22nd congressional district|CA]]).<ref name="Jacobs 1987">{{cite book|last=Jacobs|first=David C.|year=1987|editor1-last=Lewin|editor1-first=David|editor2-last=Lipsky|editor2-first=David|editor3-last=Sockell|editor3-first=Donna|chapter=The UAW and the Committee for National Health Insurance: the contours of social unionism|title=Advances in industrial and labor relations: a research annual|volume=4|location=Greenwich, Conn.|publisher=JAI Press|isbn=0-89232-909-2|pages=119–140}}</ref> In September 1970, the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Senate Labor and Public Welfare Committee]] held the first congressional hearings in twenty years on national health insurance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lyons|first=Richard D.|date=September 22, 1970|title=Senate panel to open hearings on health insurance|newspaper=The New York Times|page=33|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40616F63B5C1B7493C0AB1782D85F448785F9}}</ref>

In January 1971, Kennedy began a decade as chairman of the Health subcommittee of the Senate Labor and Public Welfare Committee, and introduced a reconciled bipartisan Kennedy-Griffiths bill proposing universal national health insurance.<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1971">{{cite book|author=.|year=1972|chapter=Health insurance: hearings on new proposals|title=Congressional Quarterly almanac, 92nd Congress 1st session....1971|volume=27|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Congressional Quarterly|pages=541–544|issn=0095-6007|oclc=1564784}}</ref> In February 1971, President [[Richard Nixon]] proposed more limited health insurance reform—a private health insurance employer mandate and federalization of [[Medicaid]] for the poor with dependent minor children.<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1971"/> Hearings on national health insurance were held by the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means Committee]] and the [[United States Senate Committee on Finance|Senate Finance Committee]] in 1971, but no bill had the support of committee chairmen Representative [[Wilbur Mills]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Arkansas's 2nd congressional district|AR]]) or Senator [[Russell B. Long|Russell Long]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[List of United States Senators from Louisiana|LA]]).<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1971"/> 

In October 1972, Nixon signed the Social Security Amendments of 1972 extending Medicare to those under 65 who have been severely disabled for over two years or have [[End Stage Renal Disease Program|end stage renal disease]] (ESRD), and gradually raising the Medicare Part A payroll tax from 1.1% to 1.45% in 1986.<ref name="SS: CQ Almanac 1972">{{cite book|author=.|year=1973|chapter=Welfare reform deleted from Social Security bill|title=Congressional Quarterly Almanac, 92nd Congress 2nd session....1972|volume=28|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Congressional Quarterly|pages=899–914|issn=0095-6007|oclc=1564784}}</ref> In November 1972, Nixon won re-election in a landslide over the only Democratic presidential nominee ever not endorsed by the AFL–CIO, Senator [[George McGovern]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[List of United States Senators from South Dakota|SD]]),<ref>{{cite news|last=Shabecoff|first=Philip|date=July 20, 1972|title=A.F.L.-C.I.O. chiefs vote neutral stand on election|newspaper=The New York Times|page=1|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60C16F63455127B93C2AB178CD85F468785F9}}</ref> who was a cosponsor of the Kennedy-Griffiths bill, but did not make national health insurance a major issue in his campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=Herbers|first=John|date=November 7, 1972|title=The campaign issues: many questions of interest to voters never got past convention debate|newspaper=The New York Times|page=23|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0910F93A591A7493C5A9178AD95F468785F9}}</ref>

In October 1973, Long and Senator [[Abraham A. Ribicoff|Abraham Ribicoff]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[List of United States Senators from Connecticut|CT]]) introduced a bipartisan bill for catastrophic health insurance coverage for workers financed by payroll taxes and federalization of Medicaid with extension to the poor without dependent minor children.<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1973">{{cite book|author=.|year=1974|chapter=National health insurance: action delayed in 1973|title=Congressional Quarterly almanac, 93rd Congress 1st session....1973|volume=29|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Congressional Quarterly|pages=508–510|issn=0095-6007|oclc=1564784}}</ref> In February 1974, Nixon proposed more comprehensive health insurance reform—an employer mandate to offer private health insurance and replacement of Medicaid by state-run health insurance plans available to all with income-based premiums and cost sharing.<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1974">{{cite book|author=.|year=1975|chapter=National health insurance: no action in 1974|title=Congressional Quarterly almanac, 93th Congress 2nd session....1974|volume=30|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Congressional Quarterly|pages=386–394|issn=0095-6007|oclc=1564784}}</ref> In April 1974, Kennedy and Mills introduced a bill for near-universal national health insurance with benefits identical to the expanded Nixon plan, both of which were criticized by labor and senior citizens organizations because of their substantial cost sharing.<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1974"/> 

In August 1974, after Nixon's resignation and President [[Gerald Ford]]'s call for health insurance reform, Mills tried to advance a compromise based on Nixon's plan, but gave up when the conservative half of his committee instead backed the limited [[American Medical Association]] (AMA) "Medicredit" voluntary tax credit plan.<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1974"/><ref name="Wainess 1999">{{cite journal|last=Wainess|first=Flint J.|date=April 1999|title=The Ways and Means of national health care reform, 1974 and beyond|journal=Journal of Health Politics, Policy and Law|volume=24|issue=2|pages=305–333|issn=0361-6878|oclc=2115780|url=http://jhppl.dukejournals.org/content/24/2/305.abstract}}</ref> In December 1974, Mills resigned as chairman of the Ways and Means Committee and was succeeded by Representative [[Al Ullman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Oregon's 2nd congressional district|OR]]), who opposed payroll tax and general federal revenue financing of national health insurance.<ref>{{citation|author=.|date=December 7, 1974|title=Albert Conrad Ullman: likely heir to Mills gives views on issues|newspaper=The New York Times|page=17|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20C17F9345F107A93C5A91789D95F408785F9}}</ref>

In January 1975, in the midst of the [[1973–75 recession|worst recession]] in the four decades since the [[Great Depression]], Ford said he would veto any health insurance reform,<ref>{{cite news|last=Auerbach|first=Stuart|date=January 15, 1975|title=Veto threat seals fate of health bill|newspaper=The Washington Post|page=A9|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/137318532.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI}}</ref> and Kennedy returned to sponsoring his original universal national health insurance bill.<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1975">{{cite book|author=.|year=1976|chapter=National health insurance|title=Congressional Quarterly almanac, 94th Congress 1st session....1975|volume=31|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Congressional Quarterly|pages=635–639|issn=0095-6007|oclc=1564784}}</ref> In April 1975, with one third of its sponsors gone after the November 1974 election,<ref>{{cite news|last=Lyons|first=Richard D.|date=November 23, 1974|title=Albert predicts House passage of health insurance bill by June|newspaper=The New York Times
|page=34|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F70A1EFB3F59137B93C1AB178AD95F408785F9}}</ref> the AMA replaced its "Medicredit" plan with an employer mandate proposal similar to Nixon's 1974 plan.<ref>{{cite news|author=.|date=April 14, 1975|title=A.M.A. backs medical care subsidy plan|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|page=1|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/611576182.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI}}</ref> In January 1976, Ford proposed adding catastrophic coverage to Medicare, offset by increased cost sharing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schmeck|first=Harold M. Jr.|date=January 22, 1976|title=Medicare: limiting the cost of major illness would benefit 3 million patients|newspaper=The New York Times|page=25|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F00D16F93B58167493C0AB178AD85F428785F9}}</ref> In April 1976, Democratic presidential candidate [[Jimmy Carter]] proposed health care reform that included key features of Kennedy's universal national health insurance bill.<ref name="Morris 1984">{{cite book|last=Morris|first=Jonas|year=1984|chapter=The Carter years|title=Searching for a cure: national health policy considered|location=New York|publisher=Pica Press|pages=92–171|isbn=0-87663-741-1}}</ref>
 
In December 1977, President Carter told Kennedy his bill must be changed to preserve a large role for private insurance companies, minimize federal spending (precluding payroll tax financing), and be phased-in so not to interfere with balancing the federal budget.<ref name="Morris 1984"/><ref name="Gottschalk 2000">{{cite book|last=Gottschalk|first=Marie|year=2000|chapter=Labor embraces a new idea: the journey from national health insurance to an employer mandate|title=The shadow welfare state: labor, business, and the politics of health care in the United States|location=Ithaca, N.Y.|publisher=ILR Press|pages=65–85|isbn=0-8014-3745-8|chapterurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=iJ5X5AT1xbYC&pg=PA79}}</ref> Kennedy and organized labor compromised and made the requested changes, but broke with Carter in July 1978 when he would not commit to pursuing a single bill with a fixed schedule for phasing-in comprehensive coverage.<ref name="Morris 1984"/><ref name="Gottschalk 2000"/>

In May 1979, Kennedy proposed a new bipartisan universal national health insurance bill—choice of competing federally-regulated private health insurance plans with no cost sharing financed by income-based premiums via an employer mandate and individual mandate, replacement of Medicaid by government payment of premiums to private insurers, and enhancement of Medicare by adding prescription drug coverage and eliminating premiums and cost sharing.<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1979">{{cite book|author=.|year=1980|chapter=National health insurance|title=Congressional Quarterly almanac, 96th Congress 1st session....1979|volume=35|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Congressional Quarterly|pages=536–540|issn=0095-6007|oclc=1564784}}</ref><ref name="Starr 2011">{{cite book|last=Starr|first=Paul|year=2011|chapter=Stumbling toward comprehensive reform: Political deadlock, 1969–1980|title=Remedy and reaction: the peculiar American struggle over health care reform|location=New Haven|publisher=Yale University Press|pages=52–63|isbn=978-0-17109-9|chapterurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=PNFLo4DWsJkC&pg=PA52}}</ref> In June 1979, Carter proposed more limited health insurance reform—an employer mandate to provide catastrophic private health insurance plus coverage without cost sharing for pregnant women and infants, federalization of Medicaid with extension to the very poor without dependent minor children, and enhancement of Medicare by adding catastrophic coverage.<ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1979"/> In November 1979, Long led a bipartisan conservative majority of his Senate Finance Committee to support an employer mandate to provide catastrophic-only private health insurance and enhancement of Medicare by adding catastrophic coverage, but abandoned efforts in May 1980 due to budget constraints in the face of a deteriorating economy.<ref name="Morris 1984"/><ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1979"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Roberts|first=Steven V.|date=December 9, 1979|title=Health bill strategy unites candidates Carter and Long|newspaper=The New York Times
|page=E5|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30A16F83D5F12728DDDA00894DA415B898BF1D3}}</ref><ref name="NHI: CQ Almanac 1980">{{cite book|author=.|year=1981|chapter=National health insurance|title=Congressional Quarterly almanac, 96th Congress 2nd session....1980|volume=36|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Congressional Quarterly|page=462|issn=0095-6007|oclc=1564784}}</ref>

==== 1980s ====
The [[Consolidated Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1985]] (COBRA) amended the [[Employee Retirement Income Security Act]] of 1974 (ERISA) to give some employees the ability to continue [[health insurance]] coverage after leaving employment.

=== Clinton initiative ===
{{see also|Health Security Express}}
<!-- This section needs expansion to balance the article -->
Health care reform was a major concern of the [[Presidency of Bill Clinton|Bill Clinton administration]] headed up by First Lady [[Hillary Clinton]]; however, the [[1993 Clinton health care plan]] was not enacted into law.  

The "Health Security Express" was a bus tour that started the end of July 1994. It involved supporters of President Clinton's national health care reform. Several buses leaving from different points in the United States, such as Portland, Oregon, and Boston, Mass crossed the country and stopped in many cities along their way to their final destination at the White House in Washington, DC on August 3, 1994. During these stops, each of the bus riders would talk about their personal experiences, health care disasters and why they felt it was important for all Americans to have health insurance.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Fisher, Mary Jane |date=August 1, 1974 |title='Health Security Express' prods Congress for reform |journal=National Underwriter. Property & casualty/risk & benefits management ed. |volume=98 |issue=31 |pages=4–5|issn=1042-6841 |url=http://www.amazon.com/Health-Security-Express-Congress-reform/dp/B00092L9YU |accessdate=October 30, 2010}}</ref> When the Health Security Express bus tour ended, all of the riders were greeted by President Clinton and the First Lady on the White House South lawn for a rally on Wednesday, August 3, 1994, which was broadcast all over the world by many international networks including C-SPAN.<ref>{{cite web |author=. |date=August 3, 1994 |title=Health Security Express (video 43:26) |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[C-SPAN]] |url=http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/59243-1 |accessdate=October 30, 2010}}</ref>

=== Bush era debates ===
