In 2000 the [[Health Insurance Association of America]] (HIAA) partnered with [[Families USA]] and the [[American Hospital Association]] (AHA) on a "strange bedfellows" proposal intended to seek common ground in expanding coverage for the uninsured.<ref>{{cite web |author=. |date=November 20, 2000 |title='Strange bedfellow' join forces on agreement for uninsured Americans (press release) |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[Families USA]] |url=http://www.familiesusa.org/resources/newsroom/press-releases/2000-press-releases/press-release-strange-bedfellows-join-forces-on-agreement-for-uninsured-americans.html |accessdate=June 19, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Kahn III, Charles N.; Pollack, Ronald F. |month=January–February |year=2001 |title=Building a consensus for expanding health coverage |journal=Health Affairs |pmid=11194859 |volume=20 |issue=1 |pages=40–48 |doi=10.1377/hlthaff.20.1.40 |url=http://content.healthaffairs.org/content/20/1/40.full.pdf |accessdate=June 19, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Meier, Conrad F. |date=April 1, 2001 |title= HIAA and Families USA seek more government |location=Chicago |publisher=[[The Heartland Institute]] |url=http://www.heartland.org/publications/health%20care/article/682/HIAA_and_Families_USA_Seek_More_Government.html |accessdate=June 19, 2009}}</ref>

In 2001, a [[U.S. Patients' Bill of Rights|Patients' Bill of Rights]] was debated in Congress, which would have provided patients with an explicit list of rights concerning their health care. This initiative was essentially taking some of ideas found in the [[Consumer Bill of Rights|Consumers' Bill of Rights]] and applying it to the field of health care. It was undertaken in an effort to ensure the quality of care of all patients by preserving the integrity of the processes that occur in the health care industry.<ref name="McCain-Edwards-Kennedy">{{cite web |author=. |year=2001 |title=Summary of the McCain-Edwards-Kennedy Patients' Bill of Rights |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[Democratic Caucus of the United States Senate|U.S. Senate Democratic Caucus]] |url=http://democrats.senate.gov/pbr/summary.html |accessdate=April 17, 2008}}</ref> Standardizing the nature of health care institutions in this manner proved rather provocative. In fact, many [[interest group]]s, including the [[American Medical Association]] (AMA) and the [[pharmaceutical industry]] came out vehemently against the congressional bill. Basically, providing emergency medical care to anyone, regardless of health insurance status, as well as the right of a patient to hold their health plan accountable for any and all harm done proved to be the biggest stumbling blocks for this bill.<ref name="McCain-Edwards-Kennedy"/> As a result of this intense opposition, the [[U.S. Patients' Bill of Rights|Patients' Bill of Rights]] initiative eventually failed to pass [[United States Congress|Congress]] in 2002.

As president, [[George W. Bush|Bush]] signed into law the [[Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement, and Modernization Act]] which included a prescription drug plan for [[elderly]] and [[disabled]] Americans.<ref>{{cite web |author=. |year=2006 |title=Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[United States Department of Health and Human Services|U.S. Department of Health and Human Services]] |url=http://cms.hhs.gov |accessdate=March 11, 2006}}</ref>

During the [[United States presidential election, 2004|2004 presidential election]], both the [[George W. Bush presidential campaign, 2004|George Bush]] and [[John Kerry presidential campaign, 2004|John Kerry]] campaigns offered health care proposals.  Bush's proposals for expanding health care coverage were more modest than those advanced by Senator Kerry.<ref>{{cite news |author=Toner, Robin |date=May 14, 2004 |title=Biggest divide? Maybe it's health care |newspaper=The New York Times |page=A18 |url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9506EEDE1F3CF937A25756C0A9629C8B63 |accessdate=June 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=editorial |date=October 3, 2004 |title=Kerry vs. Bush on health care |newspaper=The New York Times |page=WK10 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/03/opinion/03sun1.html?pagewanted=all |accessdate=June 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Connolly, Ceci |date=August 22, 2004 |title=Bush health care plan seems to fall short |newspaper=The Washington Post |page=A4 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A21929-2004Aug21.html |accessdate=June 26, 2009}}</ref> Several estimates were made comparing the cost and impact of the Bush and Kerry proposals. While the estimates varied, they all indicated that the increase in coverage and the funding requirements of the Bush plan would both be lower than those of the more comprehensive Kerry plan.<ref>{{cite web |author=Sheils, John |date=September 21, 2004 |title=Bush and Kerry health care proposals: cost and coverage compared |location=Falls Church, Va. |publisher=[[UnitedHealth Group#The Lewin Group|The Lewin Group]]  |url=http://www.lewin.com/content/publications/2983.pdf |accessdate=June 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Antos, Joseph; King, Roland (Guy); Muse, Donald; Wildsmith, Tom; Xanthopoulos, Judy |date=September 13, 2004 |title=Analyzing the Kerry and Bush health proposal: estimates of cost and impact |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[American Enterprise Institute]] (AEI) |url=http://www.aei.org/docLib/20040913_KerryBushHealthPlans.pdf |accessdate=June 26, 2009}}</ref>

In 2006 the HIAA's successor organization, [[America's Health Insurance Plans]] (AHIP), issued another set of reform proposals.<ref>{{cite web |author=. |date=November 13, 2006 |title=We believe every American should have access to affordable health care coverage: a vision for reform |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[America's Health Insurance Plans]] (AHIP) |url=http://www.ahipresearch.org/PDFs/vision_of_reform.pdf |accessdate=June 19, 2009}}</ref>

In January 2007 Rep. [[John Conyers]], Jr. (D-MI) has introduced The [[United States National Health Care Act]] (HR 676) in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]]. As of October 2008, HR 676 has 93 co-sponsors.<ref>{{cite web |author=. |date=July 29, 2008 |title=H.R. 676 - U.S.National Health Insurance Act (Expanded and Improved Medicare for All Act) - cosponsors |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[THOMAS]] ([[Library of Congress]]) |url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d110:HR00676:@@@P |accessdate=March 21, 2008}}</ref> Also in January 2007, Senator Ron Wyden introduced the [[Healthy Americans Act]] (S. 334) in the [[United States Senate|Senate]].  As of October 2008, S. 334 had 17 cosponsors.<ref>{{cite web |author=. |date=April 24, 2008 |title=S. 334 - Healthy Americans Act - bill summary & status |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[THOMAS]] ([[Library of Congress]]) |url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d110:s.00334:  |accessdate=May 5, 2008}}</ref> 

Also in 2007, AHIP issued a proposal for guaranteeing access to coverage in the individual health insurance market and a proposal for improving the quality and safety of the U.S. health care system.<ref>{{cite web |author=. |date=December 19, 2007 |title=Guaranteeing access to coverage for all Americans |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[America's Health Insurance Plans]] (AHIP) |url=http://www.ahipresearch.org/pdfs/AHIPGuaranteeAccessPlan.pdf |accessdate=June 19, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=. |date=April 19, 2007 |title=Setting a higher bar: we believe there is more the nation can do to improve quality and safety in health care |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[America's Health Insurance Plans]] (AHIP) |url=http://www.ahip.org/content/fileviewer.aspx?docid=19476&linkid=167556 |accessdate=June 19, 2009}}</ref>

"Economic Survey of the United States 2008: Health Care Reform" by the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]], published in December 2008, said that:<ref name="oecdhealthreform2008">{{cite web |author=. |date=December 9, 2008 |title=Economic survey of the United States 2008: health care reform |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|OECD]] |url=http://www.oecd.org/document/51/0,3343,en_2649_34117_41809843_1_1_1_1,00.html |accessdate=January 22, 2009}}</ref>
* Tax benefits of employer-based insurances should be abolished.
* The resulting tax revenues should be used to subsidize the purchase of insurance by individuals.
* These subsidies, "which could take many forms, such as direct subsidies or refundable tax credits, would improve the current situation in at least two ways: they would reach those who do not now receive the benefit of the tax exclusion; and they would encourage more cost-conscious purchase of health insurance plans and health care services as, in contrast to the uncapped tax exclusion, such subsidies would reduce the incentive to purchase health plans with little cost sharing."

In December 2008, the Institute for America's Future together with the chairman of the Ways and Means Health Subcommittee Pete Stark launched a proposal from Jacob Hacker who is co-director of the U.C. Berkeley School of Law Center on Health that in essence said that the government should offer a [[Public health insurance option|public health insurance plan]] to compete on a level playing field with private insurance plans.<ref>{{cite web |author=Hickey, Roger; Hacker, Jacob; Stark, Pete |date=December 17, 2008 |title=News conference: the case for public plan choice in national health reform (audio 54:33) |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[Institute for America's Future]]|url=http://institute.ourfuture.org/audio-media/2008125117/news-conference-case-public-plan-choice-national-health-reform  |accessdate=April 2, 2009}}</ref> This was said to be the basis of the Obama/Biden plan. The argument is based on three basic arguments. Firstly public plans success at managing cost control (Medicare medical spending rose 4.6% p.a. compared 7.3% for private health insurance on a like-for-like basis in the 10 years from 1997 to 2006). Secondly public insurance has better payment and quality-improvement methods based on its large databases, new payment approaches, and care-coordination strategies. Thirdly it can set a standard against which private plans must compete which would help unite the public around the principle of broadly shared risk while building greater confidence in government over the long term.<ref>{{cite web |author=Hacker, Jacob S. |date=December 17, 2008 |title=The case for public plan choice in national health reform:  key to cost control and quality coverage |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[Institute for America's Future]] |url=http://institute.ourfuture.org/files/Jacob_Hacker_Public_Plan_Choice.pdf |accessdate=April 2, 2009}}</ref>

Also in December 2008, [[America's Health Insurance Plans]] (AHIP) announced a set of proposals which included setting a national goal to reduce the projected ''growth'' in health care spending by 30%.  AHIP said that if this goal were achieved, it would result in cumulative five-year savings of $500 billion.  Among the proposals was the establishment of an independent comparative effectiveness entity that compares and evaluates the benefits, risks, and incremental costs of new drugs, devices, and biologics.<ref>{{cite web |author=Board of Directors |date=December 1, 2008 |title=Now is the time for health care reform: a proposal to achieve universal coverage, affordability, quality improvement and market reform |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[America's Health Insurance Plans]] (AHIP) |url=http://www.americanhealthsolution.org/assets/Uploads/ahipreformpolicyproposal.pdf |accessdate=April 2, 2009}}</ref> An earlier "Technical Memo" published by AHIP in June 2008 had estimated that a package of reforms involving comparative effectiveness research, health information technology (HIT), medical liability reform, "pay-for-performance" and disease management and prevention could reduce U.S. national health expenditures "by as much as 9 percent by the year 2025, compared with current baseline trends."<ref>{{cite web |author=. |date=June 11, 2008 |title=Technical memo: estimates of the potential reduction in health care costs from AHIP's affordability proposals |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[America's Health Insurance Plans]] (AHIP) |url=http://www.ahipresearch.org/PDFs/TechnicalMemo06.11.08.pdf |accessdate=June 26, 2009}}</ref>

===Debate in the 2008 presidential election===
{{Main|Health care reform in the United States presidential election, 2008}}
Both of the major party presidential candidates offered positions on health care.

[[John McCain]]'s proposals focused on open-market competition rather than government funding. At the heart of his plan were tax credits - $2,500 for individuals and $5,000 for families who do not subscribe to or do not have access to health care through their employer.  To help people who are denied coverage by insurance companies due to pre-existing conditions, McCain proposed working with states to create what he called a "Guaranteed Access Plan."<ref>{{cite web |author=Moffit, Robert E.; Owcharenko, Nina |date=October 15, 2008 |title=The McCain health care plan: more power to families |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[The Heritage Foundation]] |url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/thf_media/2008/pdf/bg2198.pdf |accessdate=October 21, 2008}}</ref>

[[Barack Obama]] called for [[universal health care]].  His health care plan called for the creation of a [[Health insurance exchange|National Health Insurance Exchange]] that would include both private insurance plans and a Medicare-like government run option.  Coverage would be guaranteed regardless of health status, and premiums would not vary based on health status either. It would have required parents to cover their children, but did not require adults to buy insurance.

''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' reported that the two plans had different philosophical focuses.  They described the purpose of the McCain plan as to "make insurance more affordable," while the purpose of the Obama plan was for "more people to have health insurance."<ref>{{cite news |author=Burling, Stacey |date=September 28, 2008 |title=Rivals' prescriptions for an ailing system |newspaper=The Philadelphia Inquirer |page=A12 |url=http://articles.philly.com/2008-09-28/news/25248749_1_health-insurance-employer-sponsored-insurance-health-care |accessdate=September 29, 2009}}</ref>  ''[[The Des Moines Register]]'' characterized the plans similarly.<ref>{{cite news |author=Leys, Tony |date=September 29, 2008 |title=Health plans pit low-cost vs. public coverage |newspaper=The Des Moines Register |page=A1 |url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/desmoinesregister/access/1697453021.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT |accessdate=September 29, 2008}}</ref>

A poll released in early November, 2008, found that voters supporting Obama listed health care as their second priority; voters supporting McCain listed it as fourth, tied with the war in Iraq.  Affordability was the primary health care priority among both sets of voters.  Obama voters were more likely than McCain voters to believe government can do much about health care costs.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Blendon, Robert J.; Altman, Drew E.; Benson, John M.; Brodie, Mollyann; Buhr, Tami; Deane, Claudia; Buscho, Sasha |date=November 6, 2008 |title=Voters and health reform in the 2008 presidential election |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |pmid=18974307 |volume=359 |issue=19 |pages=2050–2061 |doi=10.1056/NEJMsr0807717 |url=http://www.nejm.org/doi/pdf/10.1056/NEJMsr0807717 |accessdate=November 3, 2008}}</ref>

=== 2009 reform debate ===
{{main|Health care reform debate in the United States}}
In March 2009 AHIP proposed a set of reforms intended to address waste and unsustainable growth in the current health care market.  These reforms included: 
* An individual insurance mandate with a financial penalty as a quid pro quo for guaranteed issue
* Updates to the Medicare physician fee schedule;
* Setting standards and expectations for safety and quality of diagnostics;
* Promoting care coordination and patient-centered care by designating a "[[medical home]]" that would replace fragmented care with a coordinated approach to care. Physicians would receive a periodic payment for a set of defined services, such as care coordination that integrates all treatment received by a patient throughout an illness or an acute event. This would promote ongoing comprehensive care management, optimizes patients’ health status and assist patients in navigating the health care system
* Linking payment to quality, adherence to guidelines, achieving better clinical outcomes, giving better patient experience and lowering the total cost of care.
* [[Bundled payment]]s (instead of individual billing) for the management of chronic conditions in which providers would have shared accountability and responsibility for the management of chronic conditions such as coronary artery disease, diabetes, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and asthma, and similarly
* A fixed rate all-inclusive average payment for acute care episodes which tend to follow a pattern (even though some acute care episodes may cost more or less than this).<ref>{{cite web |author=Board of Directors |date=March 9, 2009 |title=Improving the U.S. health care system: rethinking the delivery and payment structures |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[America's Health Insurance Plans]] (AHIP) |url=http://www.ahip.org/content/default.aspx?bc=31|44|26308 |accessdate=April 2, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref>

On May 5, 2009, [[US Senate Finance Committee]] held hearings on Health care reform. On the panel of the "invited stakeholder", no supporter of the [[Single-payer health care]] system was invited.<ref>{{cite news |author=Adams, John S. |date=May 17, 2009 |title=Single-payer not a player |newspaper=Great Falls Tribune |location=Great Falls, Mont. |page=A1 |url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/greatfallstribune/access/1719096261.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT |accessdate=June 16, 2009}}</ref> The panel featured [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican senators]] and industry panelists who argued against any kind of expanded health care coverage.<ref name="TRNSenateHearingsProtest">{{cite news |author=Jay, Paul |date=May 8, 2009 |title= Single-payer advocates protest Senate hearing |location=Toronto |publisher=[[The Real News|TheRealNews.com]] |url=http://therealnews.com/t/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=3665 |accessdate=May 7, 2009}}</ref> The preclusion of the single payer option from the discussion caused significant protest by doctors in the audience.<ref name="TRNSenateHearingsProtest"/>

There is one bill currently before Congress but others are expected to be presented soon. A merged single bill is the likely outcome.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} The [[Affordable Health Choices Act]] is currently before the House of Representatives and the main sticking points at the markup stage of the bill have been in two areas; should the government provide a public insurance plan option to compete head to head with the private insurance sector, and secondly should comparative effectiveness research be used to contain costs met by the public providers of health care.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} Some Republicans have expressed opposition to the public insurance option believing that the government will not compete fairly with the private insurers. Republicans have also expressed opposition to the use of comparative effectiveness research to limit coverage in any public sector plan (including any public insurance scheme or any existing government scheme such as Medicare), which they regard as rationing by the back door.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} Democrats have claimed that the bill will not do this but are reluctant to introduce a clause that will prevent, arguing that it would limit the right of the DHHS to prevent payments for services that clearly do not work.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} America's Health Insurance Plans, the umbrella organization of the private health insurance providers in the United States has recently urged the use of CER to cut costs by restricting access to ineffective treatments and cost/benefit ineffective ones. Republican amendments to the bill would not prevent the private insurance sectors from citing CER to restrict coverage and apply rationing of their funds, a situation which would create a competition imbalance between the public and private sector insurers.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} A proposed but not yet enacted short bill with the same effect is the Republican sponsored [[Patients Act 2009]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}

On June 15, 2009, the [[Congressional Budget Office|U.S. Congressional Budget Office]] (CBO) issued a preliminary analysis of the major provisions of the Affordable Health Choices Act.<ref name="CBO - Prelim. Anal. of the Health Choices Act">{{cite web |author=. |date=June 15, 2009 |title=Preliminary analysis of major provisions related to health insurance coverage under the Affordable Health Choices Act |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[Congressional Budget Office]] (CBO) |url=http://www.cbo.gov/ftpdocs/103xx/doc10310/06-15-HealthChoicesAct.pdf |accessdate=June 22, 2009}}</ref> The CBO estimated the ten-year cost to the federal government of the major insurance-related provisions of the bill at approximately $1.0 trillion.<ref name="CBO - Prelim. Anal. of the Health Choices Act"/> Over the same ten-year period from 2010 to 2019, the CBO estimated that the bill would reduce the number of uninsured Americans by approximately 16 million.<ref name="CBO - Prelim. Anal. of the Health Choices Act"/> At about the same time, the [[Associated Press]] reported that the CBO had given Congressional officials an estimate of $1.6 trillion for the cost of a companion measure being developed by the Senate Finance Committee.<ref>{{cite news |author=Espo, David (Associated Press) |date=June 16, 2009 |title=Dems seek to trim health bill as estimates soar |location=Chicago |publisher=[[RealClearPolitics|RealClearPolitics.com]] |url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/news/ap/politics/2009/Jun/16/dems_seek_to_trim_health_bill_as_estimates_soar.html |accessdate=June 22, 2009}}</ref>  In response to these estimates, the Senate Finance Committee delayed action on its bill and began work on reducing the cost of the proposal to $1.0 trillion, and the debate over the Affordable Health Choices act became more acrimonious.<ref>{{cite news |author=Alonso-Zaldivar, Ricardo (Associated Press) |date=June 17, 2009 |title=Lawmakers clash over cost of health care overhaul |location=Chicago |publisher=[[RealClearPolitics|RealClearPolitics.com]]  |url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/news/ap/politics/2009/Jun/17/lawmakers_clash_over_cost_of_health_care_overhaul.html |accessdate=June 22, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Montgomery, Lori |date=June 18, 2009 |title=Debate on health care hits snags at the start |newspaper=The Washington Post |page=A4 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/17/AR2009061703490.html |accessdate=June 22, 2009}}</ref> Congressional Democrats were surprised by the magnitude of the estimates, and the uncertainty created by the estimates has increased the confidence of Republicans who are critical of the Obama Administration's approach to health care.<ref>{{cite news |author=Babington, Charles (Associated Press) |date=June 20, 2009 |title=Obama may need firmer hand on health care debate |newspaper=The Houston Chronicle |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/nation/6489587.html |accessdate=June 22, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Connolly, Ceci |date=June 19, 2009 |title=Obama initiatives hit speed bumps on Capitol Hill: high price tag for reform bill prompts sparring and a delay |newspaper=The Washington Post |page=A1 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/18/AR2009061804109. |accessdate=June 22, 2009}}</ref>

However, in a June [[The New York Times|New York Times]] editorial, economist [[Paul Krugman]] argued that despite these estimates universal health coverage is still affordable. "The fundamental fact is that we can afford universal health insurance--even those high estimates were less than the $1.8 trillion cost of the Bush tax cuts."<ref>{{cite news |author=Krugman, Paul (op-ed) |date=June 22, 2009 |title=Health care showdown |newspaper=The New York Times |page=A21 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/22/opinion/22krugman.html?_r=1&ref=opinion |accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref>

In contrast to earlier advocacy of a [[publicly funded health care]] program, in August 2009 Obama administration officials announced they would support a [[health insurance cooperative]] in response to deep political unrest amongst Congressional Republicans and amongst citizens in town hall meetings held across America.<ref>{{cite news |author=Elliott, Philip (Associated Press) |date=August 16, 2009 |title=White House appears ready to drop 'public option' |newspaper=The Houston Chronicle |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/nation/6574597.html |accessdate=August 17, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=. |date=August 16, 2009 |title=President Obama considering insurance co-op |location=Colorado Springs, Colo. |publisher=[[KKTV|KKTV.com]] ([[CBS News|CBS]]) |url=http://www.kktv.com/home/headlines/53362687.html |accessdate=August 17, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=. |date=August 16, 2009 |title=Town halls having an impact? White House bends on health care provision in face of discontent |publisher=FOXNews.com |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/08/16/town-halls-having-impact-white-house-bends-health-care-provision-face |accessdate=August 17, 2009}}</ref> However, in a June 2009 [[NBC News]]/[[Wall Street Journal]] survey, 76% said it was either "extremely" or "quite" important to "give people a choice of both a public plan administered by the federal government and a private plan for their health insurance."<ref>{{cite web |author=. |date=June 16, 2009 |title=Hart/McInturff, NBC News/Wall Street Journal survey, study #6095, June 12–15, 2009 |publisher=msnbc.com |url=http://msnbcmedia.msn.com/i/msnbc/sections/news/090617_NBC-WSJ_poll_Full.pdf |accessdate=August 18, 2009}}</ref>

During the summer of 2009, members of the [[Tea Party protests|"Tea Party"]] protested against proposed health care reforms.<ref name="Bowser">{{cite news |author=Bowser, Andre |date=August 21, 2009 |title=TEA Party protests health care reform plan |newspaper=East Valley Tribune  |location=Mesa, Ariz. |url=http://www.eastvalleytribune.com/article_1cfe6afa-af12-54b1-80f3-b51e0a61f817.html |accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref><ref name="Copeland">{{cite news |author=Copeland, Mike |date=August 15, 2009 |title= Local Tea Party members protest Obama health care plan at Chet Edwards' Waco office |newspaper=Waco Tribune-Herald |location=Waco, Tex. |url= http://www.allbusiness.com/government/government-bodies-offices-legislative/12673025-1.html |accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref><ref name=summer>{{cite news |author=Smith, Ben |date=August 21, 2009 |title=The summer of Astroturf |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico.com]] |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0809/26312.html |accessdate=August 28, 2009}}</ref> Former insurance [[public relations|PR]] executive [[Wendell Potter]] of the [[Center for Media and Democracy]]- whose funding comes from groups such as the [[Tides Foundation]]-<ref name="financial">{{cite web |author=. |year=2008 |title=Financial supporters |work=[[PR Watch]] |location=Madison, Wis. |publisher=[[Center for Media and Democracy]] |url=http://www.prwatch.org/finances.html |accessdate=September 1, 2009}}</ref> argue that the hyperbole generated by this phenomenon is a form of corporate [[astroturfing]], which he says that he used to write for [[CIGNA]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Potter, Wendell (op-ed) |date=August 17, 2009 |title=Commentary: How insurance firms drive debate |publisher=CNN.com |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/08/17/potter.health.insurance/index.html?iref=mpstoryview |accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref> Opponents of more government involvement, such as Phil Kerpen of [[Americans for Prosperity]]- whose funding comes mainly from the [[Koch Industries]] corporation<ref>{{cite web |author=Evans, Will ([[Center for Investigative Reporting]]) |date=October 6, 2008 |title=Protecting a Republican incumbent |work=Secret Money Project (blog) |publisher=[[NPR]] |url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/secretmoney/2008/10/protecting_a_republican_incumb.html  |accessdate=September 1, 2009}}</ref> counter-argue that those corporations oppose a [[Publicly funded health care|public-plan]], but some try to push for government actions that will unfairly benefit them, like employer [[Health insurance mandate|mandates]] forcing private companies to buy health insurance.<ref>{{cite news |author=Kerpen, Phil (op-ed) |date=August 12, 2009 |title=The grass is AstroTurf-er on the other side |publisher=FOXNews.com |url=http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2009/08/12/grass-astrpturf-er |accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref> Journalist [[Ben Smith (journalist)|Ben Smith]] has referred to mid-2009 as "The Summer of Astroturf" given the organizing and coordinating efforts made by various groups on both pro- and anti-reform sides.<ref name=summer/>

==State and city reform efforts==
A few states have taken serious steps toward universal health care coverage, most notably [[Minnesota]], [[Massachusetts]] and [[Connecticut]], with recent examples being the [[Massachusetts 2006 Health Reform Statute]]<ref>{{cite web |author=White, Deborah |year=2008 |title=Pros & cons of Massachusetts' mandatory health insurance program |location=New York|publisher=[[About.com]] |url=http://usliberals.about.com/od/healthcare/i/MassHealthIns.htm |accessdate=March 24, 2008}}</ref> and Connecticut's [[SustiNet]] plan to provide quality, affordable health care to state residents.<ref name="AARP">{{cite web |author=. |date=July 21, 2009 |title=In historic vote, legislature overrides SustiNet veto |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[AARP]] |url=http://cq5.share.aarp.org/content/aarp/en/home/states/ct/advocacy/articles/in_historic_vote_legislature_overrides_sustinet_veto.print.html |accessdate=September 18, 2009}}</ref> The influx of more than a quarter of a million newly insured residents has led to overcrowded waiting rooms and overworked primary-care physicians who were already in short supply in Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Moore, Pamela |month=May |year=2008 |title=Voting for healthcare reform |journal=Physicians Practice |volume=18 |issue=7 |pages=26–40 |url=http://www.physicianspractice.com/index/fuseaction/articles.details/articleID/1197/page/1.htm |accessdate=July 1, 2009}}</ref> Other states, while not attempting to insure all of their residents, cover large numbers of people by reimbursing hospitals and other health care providers using what is generally characterized as a [[charity care]] scheme; [[New Jersey]] is perhaps the best example of a state that employs the latter strategy. 

Several single payer referendums have been proposed at the state level, but so far all have failed to pass: [[California]] in 1994,<ref>{{cite web |author=Danelski, Ann E.; Altman, Drew E.; Eldred, Jan; James, Matt; Rowland, Diane |date=August 1, 1995 |title=The California single-payer debate: the defeat of Proposition 186 |location=Menlo Park, Calif. |publisher=[[Kaiser Family Foundation]] |url=http://www.kff.org/statepolicy/1075-index.cfm |accessdate=July 28, 2007}}</ref> [[Massachusetts]] in 2000, and [[Oregon]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |author=Moser, Joe |date=December 1, 2002 |title=Free-market reformers are winners in election 2002 |location=Chicago |publisher=[[The Heartland Institute]] |url=http://www.heartland.org/healthpolicy-news.org/article/10803/FreeMarket_Reformers_Are_Winners_in_Election_2002.html|accessdate=July 28, 2007}}</ref> The state legislature of California has twice passed SB 840, The Health Care for All Californians Act, a single-payer health care system. Both times, Governor [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] (R) vetoed the bill, once in 2006 and again in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |author=.  |year=2007 |title=Health Care for All - California |location=Novato, Calif. |publisher= HealthCareforAll.org |url=http://www.healthcareforall.org  |accessdate=March 20, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=. |year=2007 |title=California OneCare |location=Novato, Calif. |publisher=CaliforniaOneCare.org |url=http://www.onecarenow.org |accessdate=March 20, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=. |date=September 30, 2008 |title=S.B. 840 - California Universal Healthcare Act - Single-payer health care coverage |location=Sacramento |publisher=[[California Legislative Counsel]] |url=http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/07-08/bill/sen/sb_0801-0850/sb_840_bill_20081130_history.html |accessdate=October 1, 2008}}</ref>

The percentage of residents that are uninsured varies from state to state. [[Texas]] has the highest percentage of residents without health insurance at 24%.<ref name="KSHF">{{cite web |author=. |year=2008 |title=Health insurance coverage of the total population |work=StateHealthFacts.org |location=Menlo Park, Calif. |publisher=[[Kaiser Family Foundation]]  |url=http://www.statehealthfacts.org/comparemaptable.jsp?ind=125&cat=3&sub=39&typ=2&rgnhl=1|accessdate=May 21, 2008}}</ref> [[New Mexico]] has the second highest percentage of uninsured at 22%.<ref name="KSHF"/>

States play a variety of roles in the health care system including purchasers of health care and regulators of providers and health plans,<ref>{{cite web |author=. |year=2008 |title=Managed care & health insurance |work=StateHealthFacts.org |location=Menlo Park, Calif. |publisher=[[Kaiser Family Foundation]]  |url=http://www.statehealthfacts.org/comparecat.jsp?cat=7&rgn=6&rgn=1 |accessdate=May 21, 2008}}</ref> which give them multiple opportunities to try to improve how it functions.  While states are actively working to improve the system in a variety of ways, there remains room for them to do more.<ref>{{cite web |author=Hess, Catherine; Schwartz, Sonya; Rosenthal, Jill; Snyder, Andrew; Weil, Alan (National Academy for State Health Policy - NASHP) |date=April 10, 2008 |title=States' roles in shaping high performance health systems |location=New York |publisher=[[Commonwealth Fund|The Commonwealth Fund]] |url=http://www.commonwealthfund.org/usr_doc/Hess_statesrolesshapinghighperfhltsys_1115.pdf?section=4039 |accessdate=April 11, 2008}}</ref>

One municipality, [[San Francisco, California]], has established a program to provide health care to all uninsured residents ([[Healthy San Francisco]]).

In July 2009, [[Connecticut]] passed into law a plan called [[SustiNet]], with the goal of achieving health-care coverage of 98% of its residents by 2014.<ref name="AARP"/> The SustiNet law establishes a nine-member board to recommend to the legislature, by January 1, 2011, the details of and implementation process for a self-insured health care plan called SustiNet. The recommendations must address (1) the phased-in offering of the SustiNet plan to state employees and retirees, HUSKY A and B beneficiaries, people without employer-sponsored insurance (ESI) or with unaffordable ESI, small and large employers, and others; (2) establishing an entity that can contract with insurers and health care providers, set reimbursement rates, develop medical homes for patients, and encourage the use of health information technology; (3) a model benefits package; and (4) public outreach and ways to identify uninsured citizens.<ref name="Connecticut OLR">{{cite web |author=. |year=2009 |title=OLR - Acts affecting insurance |location=Hartford |publisher=[[Connecticut General Assembly]], Office of Legislative Research |url=http://www.cga.ct.gov/olr/Documents/year/AA/2009AA-20091014_2009%20Acts%20Affecting%20Insurance.pdf |accessdate=July 21, 2009}}</ref> The board must establish committees to make recommendations to it about health information technology, medical homes, clinical care and safety guidelines, and preventive care and improved health outcomes. The act also establishes an independent information clearinghouse to inform employers, consumers, and the public about SustiNet and private health care plans and creates task forces to address obesity, tobacco usage, and health care workforce issues. The effective date of the SustiNet law was July 1, 2009, for most provisions.<ref name="Connecticut OLR"/>

In May 2011, the state of Vermont became the first state to pass legislation establishing a Single-Payer health care system. The legislation, known as Act 48, establishes health care in the state as a "human right" and lays the responsibility on the state to provide a health care system which best meets the needs of the citizens of Vermont. The state is currently in the studying phase of how best to implement this system.

